1
0:0:1,0 --> 0:3:40,587
Downloaded From www.AllSubs.org


2
0:3:40,587 --> 0:3:43,423
Judd, you can't.


3
0:3:43,423 --> 0:3:45,391
I got to
get in the house.


4
0:3:45,391 --> 0:3:49,929
Poke your head out in the
clear, and a Falin will get you.


5
0:3:49,929 --> 0:4:13,486
But Melissa,
she's going to have a baby.


6
0:4:13,486 --> 0:4:14,854
Hit you, David?


7
0:4:14,854 --> 0:4:45,18
No Falin can ever
get me, Uncle Judd.


8
0:4:45,18 --> 0:4:50,456
Oh, God, give her the strength to be good,


9
0:4:50,456 --> 0:4:56,195
to be never hateful
and never fight.


10
0:4:56,195 --> 0:4:59,866
And don't let her
carry the burden of fear,


11
0:4:59,866 --> 0:5:5,938
watching her loved ones
and seeing them die.


12
0:5:5,938 --> 0:5:9,242
Always asking
out of her heart,


13
0:5:9,242 --> 0:5:40,973
"Why has it got to be?
Why has it got to be?"


14
0:5:40,973 --> 0:5:47,213
<i>When it's twilight</i>
<i>on the trail</i>


15
0:5:47,213 --> 0:5:50,45
<i>And I jog along</i>


16
0:5:50,45 --> 0:5:53,252
<i>The world is like a dream</i>


17
0:5:53,252 --> 0:5:59,425
<i>And the ripple of the stream</i>
<i>is my song</i>


18
0:5:59,425 --> 0:6:5,164
<i>When it's twilight</i>
<i>on the trail</i>


19
0:6:5,164 --> 0:6:8,568
<i>And I rest once more</i>


20
0:6:8,568 --> 0:6:11,137
<i>My ceiling is the sky</i>


21
0:6:11,137 --> 0:6:17,91
<i>And the grass on which I lie</i>
<i>is my floor</i>


22
0:6:17,91 --> 0:6:23,716
<i>Never ever</i> <i>have a
nickel</i> <i>in my jeans</i>


23
0:6:23,716 --> 0:6:29,188
<i>Never ever</i>
<i>have a debt to pay</i>


24
0:6:29,188 --> 0:6:35,361
<i>Still I understand</i>
<i>what real contentment means</i>


25
0:6:35,361 --> 0:6:41,2
<i>Guess I was born that way</i>


26
0:6:41,2 --> 0:6:47,74
<i>When it's twilight</i>
<i>on the trail</i>


27
0:6:47,74 --> 0:6:51,677
<i>And my voice is still</i>


28
0:6:51,677 --> 0:6:55,181
<i>Please plant</i>
<i>this heart of mine</i>


29
0:6:55,181 --> 0:7:2,321
<i>Underneath</i> <i>the Lonesome
Pine</i> <i>on the hill</i>


30
0:7:2,321 --> 0:7:4,29
And I says to him, I says,
"Look here, Zeke Denker,


31
0:7:4,29 --> 0:7:6,826
"you're driving your hogs
to mighty poor swill."


32
0:7:6,826 --> 0:7:8,594
Bet that buttoned him.
Not Zeke.


33
0:7:8,594 --> 0:7:11,497
He's the laughingest man I
ever met. Nothing bites him.


34
0:7:11,497 --> 0:7:13,266
Laughs when it's clever enough to rain.


35
0:7:13,266 --> 0:7:14,967
Laughs when
the sun shines.


36
0:7:14,967 --> 0:7:18,171
He looks me
right in the eye...


37
0:7:18,171 --> 0:7:19,872
Dave's better.


38
0:7:19,872 --> 0:7:22,308
Is he?
Yep.


39
0:7:22,308 --> 0:7:25,812
Perking up a mite.
Arm's a little green


40
0:7:25,812 --> 0:7:28,14
but I stuck a chaw
of tobaccy on it.


41
0:7:28,14 --> 0:7:30,349
Cold rifle barrel
will do it more good.


42
0:7:30,349 --> 0:7:33,52
What he have to say?
About the Falins I mean.


43
0:7:33,52 --> 0:7:36,722
"Eat your sow belly and get
for home." That's what he said.


44
0:7:36,722 --> 0:7:39,258
Said, "Ain't gonna be no
fighting till I can tote a gun."


45
0:7:39,258 --> 0:7:40,46
And I come six miles.


46
0:7:40,46 --> 0:7:41,627
Six miles.


47
0:7:41,627 --> 0:7:43,996
I can throw a clump
of dogwood that far.


48
0:7:43,996 --> 0:7:48,201
I'm nigh on to 30 miles.
Look. Look.


49
0:7:48,201 --> 0:7:50,303
Gather around now.
Gather around.


50
0:7:50,303 --> 0:7:52,371
I'm really going to
show you something now.


51
0:7:52,371 --> 0:7:55,41
Maybe we's will
get a go at the kid.


52
0:7:55,41 --> 0:7:59,178
Whenever Judd Tolliver gets
an itch to plug the Falins,


53
0:7:59,178 --> 0:8:3,216
he starts playing
with the young ones.


54
0:8:3,216 --> 0:8:5,651
I'm gonna be
the human hub.


55
0:8:5,651 --> 0:8:13,92
Now, Willie, you go down there and
stop me if I get to going too fast.


56
0:8:13,92 --> 0:8:18,3
Lizzie Bee, you better
go down and help Willie.


57
0:8:18,3 --> 0:8:31,21
Look out now, here I come.
Don't forget to stop me.


58
0:8:31,21 --> 0:8:41,988
Well, why didn't
you stop me?


59
0:8:41,988 --> 0:8:52,532
Judd's better than that
wagon show we saw once.


60
0:8:52,532 --> 0:8:57,103
Melissa, you got a bellyache or something?


61
0:8:57,103 --> 0:8:58,938
Just thinking, Lina.


62
0:8:58,938 --> 0:9:0,706
Sakes and sassafras!


63
0:9:0,706 --> 0:9:2,575
Thinking
boils the pot over.


64
0:9:2,575 --> 0:9:7,613
It boils over and over and
over if you ain't thinking.


65
0:9:7,613 --> 0:9:11,35
Killing.
All the time killing.


66
0:9:11,35 --> 0:9:13,986
They are planning it now.
They done it yesterday,


67
0:9:13,986 --> 0:9:16,522
and the week before,
and the year before that.


68
0:9:16,522 --> 0:9:19,525
Ever since I was a little child they done it.


69
0:9:19,525 --> 0:9:21,494
Kill a Falin.
Kill a Falin.


70
0:9:21,494 --> 0:9:23,229
That's all they could say.


71
0:9:23,229 --> 0:9:26,332
Plowing, splitting reins.
Filling the corn crib.


72
0:9:26,332 --> 0:9:30,736
Kill a Falin! And the echo comes
back to us from over the hills.


73
0:9:30,736 --> 0:9:35,241
Kill a Tolliver.
Kill. Kill. Why?


74
0:9:35,241 --> 0:9:42,548
Melissa!


75
0:9:42,548 --> 0:9:45,117
What you biting
your paws about, Auntie?


76
0:9:45,117 --> 0:9:47,954
Worrying, I guess, June
and Buddie ain't back yet.


77
0:9:47,954 --> 0:9:49,455
Where they be?


78
0:9:49,455 --> 0:9:57,597
Over at the yard doctor,
getting a potion for you.


79
0:9:57,597 --> 0:10:3,235
Is that the way
you like it?


80
0:10:3,235 --> 0:10:4,303
Just right.


81
0:10:4,303 --> 0:10:7,239
You should have let me
get a town doctor, Dave.


82
0:10:7,239 --> 0:10:10,543
It don't look right.
It's too swole up.


83
0:10:10,543 --> 0:10:11,911
You're awfully
good to me, Auntie.


84
0:10:11,911 --> 0:10:13,546
You're a good boy, Dave.


85
0:10:13,546 --> 0:10:15,14
Your boy.


86
0:10:15,14 --> 0:10:16,449
My boy.


87
0:10:16,449 --> 0:10:18,618
Sometimes I wished I was,
Auntie. Then I wished I wasn't


88
0:10:18,618 --> 0:10:23,122
'cause if I was, I couldn't
marry June and if I wasn't...


89
0:10:23,122 --> 0:10:25,791
Relations like we ones
got me all thicked up.


90
0:10:25,791 --> 0:10:30,463
Cousins are always thicker than
fleas in the mountains, Dave.


91
0:10:30,463 --> 0:10:35,34
I'm a big, big
black bear.


92
0:10:35,34 --> 0:10:42,808
I'm a mean black bear.


93
0:10:42,808 --> 0:10:54,2
I'm getting closer.
I'll get you.


94
0:10:54,2 --> 0:11:10,903
I'm coming closer.


95
0:11:10,903 --> 0:11:14,206
You laugh at me, foreigner,
and I'll... I'll...


96
0:11:14,206 --> 0:11:27,787
I don't blame you, I'd
do the same thing myself.


97
0:11:27,787 --> 0:11:30,356
That was funny.
Why didn't you laugh?


98
0:11:30,356 --> 0:11:31,657
She's one of
the Tollivers.


99
0:11:31,657 --> 0:11:32,892
That's still funny.


100
0:11:32,892 --> 0:11:34,26
She didn't think so.


101
0:11:34,26 --> 0:11:35,795
That's a woman's privilege.


102
0:11:35,795 --> 0:11:36,996
Now, where were we?


103
0:11:36,996 --> 0:11:38,397
Right in the middle of
that fault, over there.


104
0:11:38,397 --> 0:11:39,565
Yeah.


105
0:11:39,565 --> 0:11:42,635
Two years supply of strip-coal
before we have to drift mine it.


106
0:11:42,635 --> 0:11:43,869
We'll steam-shovel
the top coal


107
0:11:43,869 --> 0:11:46,172
and make it pay for
the railroad up here.


108
0:11:46,172 --> 0:11:47,54
You haven't got it yet.


109
0:11:47,54 --> 0:11:48,674
No.


110
0:11:48,674 --> 0:11:50,209
Well, suppose you let me worry about that.


111
0:11:50,209 --> 0:11:54,58
The right and title to that
privilege is yours, my friend.


112
0:11:54,58 --> 0:11:56,882
You got that privilege
this very minute.


113
0:11:56,882 --> 0:12:3,189
Start using it.


114
0:12:3,189 --> 0:12:4,724
I was just
running in that wood,


115
0:12:4,724 --> 0:12:6,559
and I heard
she was a bear.


116
0:12:6,559 --> 0:12:8,694
And when I looked
around to see if she


117
0:12:8,694 --> 0:12:10,296
was going to eat me,
she was gone.


118
0:12:10,296 --> 0:12:12,732
Maybe she ate herself
and disappeared.


119
0:12:12,732 --> 0:12:15,434
Judd Tolliver,
how you talk.


120
0:12:15,434 --> 0:12:18,404
Child. Child. You mustn't.


121
0:12:18,404 --> 0:12:20,172
Juny's coming back.


122
0:12:20,172 --> 0:12:31,417
Maybe she stopped
down by the river.


123
0:12:31,417 --> 0:12:33,753
Looks like she fetched
the river with her.


124
0:12:33,753 --> 0:12:35,54
June!


125
0:12:35,54 --> 0:12:36,489
Well, I brung it,
didn't I?


126
0:12:36,489 --> 0:12:38,424
June, if you ain't
the lookingest...


127
0:12:38,424 --> 0:12:39,759
I've been running
across that log


128
0:12:39,759 --> 0:12:41,961
ever since I was knee high to a grasshopper.


129
0:12:41,961 --> 0:12:44,29
I can catch a squirrel
on it with one hand,


130
0:12:44,29 --> 0:12:45,564
but when that dog
see that foreigner...


131
0:12:45,564 --> 0:12:47,199
Foreigner?


132
0:12:47,199 --> 0:12:50,136
He stopped right smack-dab in the
middle of the log and I tripped.


133
0:12:50,136 --> 0:12:51,637
What was
the foreigner doing?


134
0:12:51,637 --> 0:12:53,839
Don't know.
Wasn't looking.


135
0:12:53,839 --> 0:12:56,342
Before you know it, there
I go. Plunk, right down.


136
0:12:56,342 --> 0:12:57,643
What did he look like?


137
0:12:57,643 --> 0:12:58,911
Just had a squint.


138
0:12:58,911 --> 0:13:3,482
He's about so tall,
about that wide.


139
0:13:3,482 --> 0:13:5,851
Was all dressed in brown,
even his hat.


140
0:13:5,851 --> 0:13:7,353
And his coat had a belt.


141
0:13:7,353 --> 0:13:9,121
Just a squint?


142
0:13:9,121 --> 0:13:10,589
Dave Tolliver,
if you're thinking


143
0:13:10,589 --> 0:13:12,24
what I'm a thinking, I'm
going to tell you off.


144
0:13:12,24 --> 0:13:14,794
Go down to the creek
and wash your dirty face.


145
0:13:14,794 --> 0:13:16,929
For two carrot seeds,
I'd rub it all over you.


146
0:13:16,929 --> 0:13:19,231
You do it, and I'll spank you where it hurts.


147
0:13:19,231 --> 0:13:24,436
You will, will you?


148
0:13:24,436 --> 0:13:27,606
Did that hurt?


149
0:13:27,606 --> 0:13:29,408
How could it?


150
0:13:29,408 --> 0:13:33,279
Oh!


151
0:13:33,279 --> 0:13:35,915
I've been talking
to your pappy.


152
0:13:35,915 --> 0:13:39,819
We's going to get married.


153
0:13:39,819 --> 0:13:41,53
When?
Hog killing time.


154
0:13:41,53 --> 0:13:42,521
Your pappy has invited all the Tollivers.


155
0:13:42,521 --> 0:13:44,857
The whole kit
and boodle of them.


156
0:13:44,857 --> 0:13:46,692
I ain't marrying
till green up.


157
0:13:46,692 --> 0:13:48,527
Spring's always
the time to do them things.


158
0:13:48,527 --> 0:13:52,832
Then it'll be next green up and the next.


159
0:13:52,832 --> 0:13:55,301
I don't feel nothing.


160
0:13:55,301 --> 0:13:59,171
Like... What do you mean?


161
0:13:59,171 --> 0:14:4,51
I don't know.


162
0:14:4,51 --> 0:14:7,78
Come on. Come on.


163
0:14:7,78 --> 0:14:9,215
Dinner.


164
0:14:9,215 --> 0:14:12,218
Come on.


165
0:14:12,218 --> 0:14:13,953
Better make it just a dipping, June, or them


166
0:14:13,953 --> 0:14:16,322
hungry mouths
will eat that table bare.


167
0:14:16,322 --> 0:14:22,194
Ma. Come here.


168
0:14:22,194 --> 0:14:26,599
Ma. Do I...


169
0:14:26,599 --> 0:14:28,767
Do I like Dave?


170
0:14:28,767 --> 0:14:32,771
Why, honey,
I think you do.


171
0:14:32,771 --> 0:14:37,676
Like you like Pappy?


172
0:14:37,676 --> 0:14:44,283
Well, you remember when
Dave went to Pokey Wells,


173
0:14:44,283 --> 0:14:47,152
you was a-grieving for him
then, weren't you?


174
0:14:47,152 --> 0:14:51,29
And when he's to home, he
don't make no nevermind to you?


175
0:14:51,29 --> 0:14:53,92
But, Ma...
Melissa,


176
0:14:53,92 --> 0:14:54,927
the folks are waiting for their dinner.


177
0:14:54,927 --> 0:14:56,862
Coming.


178
0:14:56,862 --> 0:16:17,843
Well, that's
liking, honey.


179
0:16:17,843 --> 0:16:20,79
This here man wants
to talk to you, Judd.


180
0:16:20,79 --> 0:16:21,413
Does, huh?


181
0:16:21,413 --> 0:16:25,651
My name is Hale,
Jack Hale.


182
0:16:25,651 --> 0:16:27,853
I wonder if I could
see you alone.


183
0:16:27,853 --> 0:16:29,121
Here's all right.


184
0:16:29,121 --> 0:16:32,24
Well, I...


185
0:16:32,24 --> 0:16:38,97
You see, I wanted to
talk to you about coal.


186
0:16:38,97 --> 0:16:40,899
The coal on your property,
I mean.


187
0:16:40,899 --> 0:16:43,2
You know what I mean? The
fault down about a mile.


188
0:16:43,2 --> 0:16:45,904
Well, you've seen the coal.
You know what I mean.


189
0:16:45,904 --> 0:16:51,377
The fault. The Alton people,
I'm with them and they...


190
0:16:51,377 --> 0:16:53,45
You was talking
about coal.


191
0:16:53,45 --> 0:16:54,279
Oh, yes. Coal.


192
0:16:54,279 --> 0:16:55,848
There'll be a railroad
up along the Ticopi


193
0:16:55,848 --> 0:16:57,549
and then down across the ridge to your place.


194
0:16:57,549 --> 0:16:58,784
Who said there would?


195
0:16:58,784 --> 0:17:0,452
I mean, of course,
if it's agreeable with


196
0:17:0,452 --> 0:17:2,755
the contracting parties,
like yourself.


197
0:17:2,755 --> 0:17:4,857
The thing will make you rich.
There's no doubt about that.


198
0:17:4,857 --> 0:17:6,25
And if we can
make a deal...


199
0:17:6,25 --> 0:17:8,66
Who's the others?


200
0:17:8,66 --> 0:17:10,796
The contract with you
is for the coal.


201
0:17:10,796 --> 0:17:12,97
Who is the others?


202
0:17:12,97 --> 0:17:22,307
Well, there's several
other people, but mainly...


203
0:17:22,307 --> 0:17:23,375
How long have you had that?


204
0:17:23,375 --> 0:17:24,877
You ain't
answered me yet.


205
0:17:24,877 --> 0:17:26,745
When did this arm begin to show that color?


206
0:17:26,745 --> 0:17:30,582
Three days ago now,
I think.


207
0:17:30,582 --> 0:17:33,318
Get me some
warm water, quick.


208
0:17:33,318 --> 0:17:34,887
It ain't bad, is it?


209
0:17:34,887 --> 0:17:37,389
Bad?
It's gangrenous infection.


210
0:17:37,389 --> 0:17:39,24
The flesh,
it's rotting, it's dying.


211
0:17:39,24 --> 0:17:40,325
You ain't no doctor.


212
0:17:40,325 --> 0:17:42,461
You wanna live,
don't you?


213
0:17:42,461 --> 0:17:44,43
Why didn't you get this man to a doctor? Did.


214
0:17:44,43 --> 0:17:46,265
There it be. Snake brew.
You fool.


215
0:17:46,265 --> 0:17:49,701
He'll die if something isn't done.


216
0:17:49,701 --> 0:17:52,104
Am I dying, Judd?


217
0:17:52,104 --> 0:17:53,906
Sure.


218
0:17:53,906 --> 0:17:56,508
Better start making
the pine box, I guess.


219
0:17:56,508 --> 0:18:2,514
That's just what you will be
doing if something isn't done.


220
0:18:2,514 --> 0:18:3,882
Now listen to me.


221
0:18:3,882 --> 0:18:5,918
Once an infection like
this sets in, it kills.


222
0:18:5,918 --> 0:18:8,921
The only possible cure is
to cut it out, and then pray.


223
0:18:8,921 --> 0:18:10,756
Now do you understand?


224
0:18:10,756 --> 0:18:13,358
No. No.
They don't understand.


225
0:18:13,358 --> 0:18:16,395
They don't understand nothing
but shooting and killing.


226
0:18:16,395 --> 0:18:18,297
That's all they understand.
Melissa.


227
0:18:18,297 --> 0:18:21,633
I been begging you to get a
doctor, but no, you got to plan.


228
0:18:21,633 --> 0:18:26,505
You got to scheme, you got to
figure out how to kill. All of you.


229
0:18:26,505 --> 0:18:29,942
Your crops could rot
and your cattle starve.


230
0:18:29,942 --> 0:18:32,778
And you wouldn't care as long as
you was back of a squirrel rifle,


231
0:18:32,778 --> 0:18:36,482
and here was a Falin
at the other end of it.


232
0:18:36,482 --> 0:18:40,586
Now it's getting back at you. He's dying.


233
0:18:40,586 --> 0:18:45,357
You heard him say it.
My Davie's dying.


234
0:18:45,357 --> 0:18:54,933
Melissa.


235
0:18:54,933 --> 0:18:57,269
Here.


236
0:18:57,269 --> 0:18:58,37
I'm sorry,
I didn't know...


237
0:18:58,37 --> 0:19:2,441
Here.


238
0:19:2,441 --> 0:19:3,976
Get me a cloth,
a tourniquet.


239
0:19:3,976 --> 0:19:9,448
Something to tighten around his
arm and shut off the circulation.


240
0:19:9,448 --> 0:19:13,118
Get me some small knives,
the sharpest you've got.


241
0:19:13,118 --> 0:19:18,423
Get that fire going. Heat the
knives till they're white-hot.


242
0:19:18,423 --> 0:19:42,681
Keep that down and help me steady his arm.


243
0:19:42,681 --> 0:19:44,516
This is going to hurt.
We have no anesthetic.


244
0:19:44,516 --> 0:19:49,421
Something to put you to sleep, I mean.


245
0:19:49,421 --> 0:19:52,691
Better stouting up the corn
liquor with a little pepper.


246
0:19:52,691 --> 0:20:4,469
Looks like
I'm gonna need it.


247
0:20:4,469 --> 0:20:9,208
<i>Ain't got no money,</i>
<i>nowhere to spend it</i>


248
0:20:9,208 --> 0:20:13,812
<i>Ain't got no wife,</i>
<i>too independent</i>


249
0:20:13,812 --> 0:20:19,284
<i>Ain't got no mule</i>
<i>to ride around</i>


250
0:20:19,284 --> 0:20:24,656
<i>It's just because</i> <i>I'm
the poorest man</i> <i>in town</i>


251
0:20:24,656 --> 0:20:29,94
<i>Poor me</i>
<i>Poor me</i>


252
0:20:29,94 --> 0:20:33,665
<i>I wonder</i> <i>when I'm
gonna</i> <i>end this misery</i>


253
0:20:33,665 --> 0:20:35,667
I made up that
last line myself.


254
0:20:35,667 --> 0:20:37,869
Yeah? That's what
it sounded like.


255
0:20:37,869 --> 0:20:40,472
Thinking maybe you might have
a job for me, so I moseyed up.


256
0:20:40,472 --> 0:20:43,609
Well, mosey down,
and the quicker the better.


257
0:20:43,609 --> 0:20:44,977
What you got your back up for, mister?


258
0:20:44,977 --> 0:20:48,814
Go on, get on.


259
0:20:48,814 --> 0:20:51,316
They're talking
down in town as to how


260
0:20:51,316 --> 0:20:53,85
your boss saved
Dave Tolliver's life.


261
0:20:53,85 --> 0:20:55,52
That so?
Yes, the idiot.


262
0:20:55,52 --> 0:20:57,89
Two minutes
after he'd met him,


263
0:20:57,89 --> 0:20:59,558
he's carving his initials
in the fellow's arm.


264
0:20:59,558 --> 0:21:1,96
And does it get him anything? It does not.


265
0:21:1,96 --> 0:21:3,428
The whole thing's a washout.


266
0:21:3,428 --> 0:21:5,631
No coal, no railroad.


267
0:21:5,631 --> 0:21:13,5
And as for this Judd Tolliver, he's
just an ungrateful chunk of dry rot.


268
0:21:13,5 --> 0:21:14,64
They didn't ask him,
did they?


269
0:21:14,64 --> 0:21:16,942
Ask him what?


270
0:21:16,942 --> 0:21:18,51
To save Dave's life.


271
0:21:18,51 --> 0:21:21,947
Of course they didn't,
you walking phonograph.


272
0:21:21,947 --> 0:21:25,83
But what's that
got to do with it?


273
0:21:25,83 --> 0:21:28,887
We ones
is funny people.


274
0:21:28,887 --> 0:21:35,861
Mmm. Elderberries.


275
0:21:35,861 --> 0:21:48,64
Elderberries?


276
0:21:48,64 --> 0:21:50,475
Okay, partner, here's
where I get off the train.


277
0:21:50,475 --> 0:21:52,177
Ain't I gonna
see you no more?


278
0:21:52,177 --> 0:21:54,846
Well, I don't know.


279
0:21:54,846 --> 0:21:56,682
Not unless your dad
changes his mind.


280
0:21:56,682 --> 0:21:58,583
Now, don't you think
you'd better run along home?


281
0:21:58,583 --> 0:22:1,52
First, could I put my arms around you?


282
0:22:1,52 --> 0:22:4,289
Can you?
I'll say you can.


283
0:22:4,289 --> 0:22:6,525
Say, you won't forget
your lesson, will you?


284
0:22:6,525 --> 0:22:7,693
Uh-uh.


285
0:22:7,693 --> 0:22:9,728
Book learning
is good for people


286
0:22:9,728 --> 0:22:12,64
because it makes them build
what's inside of them.


287
0:22:12,64 --> 0:22:13,665
Swell.


288
0:22:13,665 --> 0:22:17,169
Some day I'm gonna build a
automobile, I'm gonna build a plane...


289
0:22:17,169 --> 0:22:18,637
Whoa! Wait a minute.
Wait a minute.


290
0:22:18,637 --> 0:22:20,205
And all those things
you told me about.


291
0:22:20,205 --> 0:22:21,306
Well, if you're
gonna do all that,


292
0:22:21,306 --> 0:22:24,76
you'd better go home
and start studying.


293
0:22:24,76 --> 0:22:25,577
Bye.
Goodbye.


294
0:22:25,577 --> 0:22:31,95
Come on, Tuffy,
grab the coal car.


295
0:22:31,95 --> 0:22:45,364
There you go.


296
0:22:45,364 --> 0:22:48,533
Well?


297
0:22:48,533 --> 0:22:49,801
Pappy wants to see you.


298
0:22:49,801 --> 0:22:52,237
He saw me,
I'm sorry to say.


299
0:22:52,237 --> 0:22:55,34
He changed his mind.


300
0:22:55,34 --> 0:22:57,42
You mean
he'll sign the agreement?


301
0:22:57,42 --> 0:23:4,483
Oh, boy. Oh, boy.


302
0:23:4,483 --> 0:23:6,351
Wait a minute.
This isn't a gag, is it?


303
0:23:6,351 --> 0:23:7,486
A what?


304
0:23:7,486 --> 0:23:9,721
Skip it.
I'll take a chance.


305
0:23:9,721 --> 0:23:20,499
This way. It's shorter.


306
0:23:20,499 --> 0:23:23,668
<i>Love is everywhere</i>


307
0:23:23,668 --> 0:23:29,608
<i>Its music fills the air</i>


308
0:23:29,608 --> 0:23:31,343
You gonna
talk to me now?


309
0:23:31,343 --> 0:23:34,212
Not a chance. Not even if your
father signed 40 contracts.


310
0:23:34,212 --> 0:23:35,614
I'm just as stubborn
as you are, young lady.


311
0:23:35,614 --> 0:23:37,649
And not word you get out of
me until you've apologized.


312
0:23:37,649 --> 0:23:38,817
I didn't do nothing.


313
0:23:38,817 --> 0:23:40,852
You didn't do nothing?
What do you call nothing?


314
0:23:40,852 --> 0:23:43,422
You were going to spit in my
eyes. You stomped on my foot.


315
0:23:43,422 --> 0:23:45,757
And when I tried to teach Buddie
his ABCs, you laughed at me.


316
0:23:45,757 --> 0:23:52,364
And you call that
nothing?


317
0:23:52,364 --> 0:23:54,65
Oh, my!
What a nice pretty.


318
0:23:54,65 --> 0:23:55,233
Where'd you get it?


319
0:23:55,233 --> 0:23:56,468
It's just a...
Can I have it?


320
0:23:56,468 --> 0:23:57,536
Why...


321
0:23:57,536 --> 0:24:1,573
I can?
Well, ain't that sweet?


322
0:24:1,573 --> 0:24:3,241
What do you say
to apologize?


323
0:24:3,241 --> 0:24:6,578
Just say, "Mr. Hale, I regret
exceedingly my unfortunate error."


324
0:24:6,578 --> 0:24:7,712
Them's hard words.


325
0:24:7,712 --> 0:24:15,554
All right.
Say it your own way.


326
0:24:15,554 --> 0:24:17,55
I regret.


327
0:24:17,55 --> 0:24:19,9
You regret what?


328
0:24:19,9 --> 0:24:23,361
I'm apologizing.


329
0:24:23,361 --> 0:24:24,729
All right. What do
you wanna talk about?


330
0:24:24,729 --> 0:24:26,465
Don't make no difference.


331
0:24:26,465 --> 0:24:27,899
All right.
Let's talk about you.


332
0:24:27,899 --> 0:24:30,135
I'd like that.


333
0:24:30,135 --> 0:24:33,371
Well, some day very soon now,
your father will have money,


334
0:24:33,371 --> 0:24:35,173
and you'll be
married to Dave.


335
0:24:35,173 --> 0:24:37,342
And what a lucky girl
you are.


336
0:24:37,342 --> 0:24:38,977
And all this
around here will be...


337
0:24:38,977 --> 0:24:40,579
Well, maybe over there
will be a big house


338
0:24:40,579 --> 0:24:46,351
and with a lawn
way down to here, and...


339
0:24:46,351 --> 0:24:48,253
Did you ever see
a grasshopper real close?


340
0:24:48,253 --> 0:24:50,455
Have him spit in my eye?
Not me.


341
0:24:50,455 --> 0:24:52,891
You see that little yellow spot on its leg?


342
0:24:52,891 --> 0:24:54,659
Well, if you touch it,
you know what will happen?


343
0:24:54,659 --> 0:24:55,961
No. I give up. What?


344
0:24:55,961 --> 0:24:57,529
Its leg will pop off.


345
0:24:57,529 --> 0:25:0,765
You little savage.


346
0:25:0,765 --> 0:25:2,67
Am I?


347
0:25:2,67 --> 0:25:4,503
Yes, you are. And when I
see Dave, I'm gonna tell him.


348
0:25:4,503 --> 0:25:6,605
Let's walk. It's a mite near a mile here.


349
0:25:6,605 --> 0:25:7,706
A mile?


350
0:25:7,706 --> 0:25:9,875
I thought you said
this was a shortcut.


351
0:25:9,875 --> 0:25:19,15
Did I?


352
0:25:19,15 --> 0:25:20,619
"Its successors
and assigns forever,


353
0:25:20,619 --> 0:25:23,388
"all mines, veins,
seams and beds of coal


354
0:25:23,388 --> 0:25:25,59
"and all other minerals
whatsoever already found


355
0:25:25,59 --> 0:25:27,692
"or which may
hereafter be found


356
0:25:27,692 --> 0:25:31,263
"upon or under all that certain
tract, piece or parcel of land


357
0:25:31,263 --> 0:25:32,998
"situate, lying
and being in the..."


358
0:25:32,998 --> 0:25:34,666
Slow down, man.


359
0:25:34,666 --> 0:25:38,3
Them squirrel tracks and chicken
scratches don't mean nothing to me.


360
0:25:38,3 --> 0:25:39,671
You trying to tell me
and Judd your coal


361
0:25:39,671 --> 0:25:41,306
won't be disruptious
to our corn?


362
0:25:41,306 --> 0:25:42,641
Is that what
you're trying to tell us?


363
0:25:42,641 --> 0:25:44,175
That's right.


364
0:25:44,175 --> 0:25:45,977
And we get quite
a toting of money?


365
0:25:45,977 --> 0:25:49,47
$5,000 in 30 days and a percentage
of the company's earnings.


366
0:25:49,47 --> 0:25:50,482
What's that percentage?


367
0:25:50,482 --> 0:25:53,618
It's like pigs, Pappy. You get one
out of six for taking care of them.


368
0:25:53,618 --> 0:25:55,754
Oh! Figures sensible.


369
0:25:55,754 --> 0:26:0,325
Mr. Hale, is this the kind of
steam shovel you told me about?


370
0:26:0,325 --> 0:26:1,726
Yes, but you look
in the back, Buddie,


371
0:26:1,726 --> 0:26:3,528
and you'll find
a great big one.


372
0:26:3,528 --> 0:26:5,13
I'll give...
Dave says it's sensible.


373
0:26:5,13 --> 0:26:6,698
I guess it's sensible.


374
0:26:6,698 --> 0:26:8,633
But there's
one thing eating me.


375
0:26:8,633 --> 0:26:9,801
What's that,
Mr. Tolliver?


376
0:26:9,801 --> 0:26:11,369
Is there no other way
for you to build


377
0:26:11,369 --> 0:26:13,471
your railroad
up to our place,


378
0:26:13,471 --> 0:26:15,6
except across the Falins?


379
0:26:15,6 --> 0:26:17,242
But it won't be the Falins. The
company will own the property.


380
0:26:17,242 --> 0:26:19,11
Yeah, but it were
the Falins.


381
0:26:19,11 --> 0:26:21,646
They walked on it. They
drove the sheep across it.


382
0:26:21,646 --> 0:26:23,381
The spring water
down by the Knuckle,


383
0:26:23,381 --> 0:26:25,383
they put their
poisonous faces in it.


384
0:26:25,383 --> 0:26:27,319
It's got the
Falins' smell on it.


385
0:26:27,319 --> 0:26:30,255
And me ones will make money going on it? No.


386
0:26:30,255 --> 0:26:32,9
No. There ain't
gonna be a Tolliver...


387
0:26:32,9 --> 0:26:35,627
It ain't gonna stop you from
shooting the dirty swine, is it?


388
0:26:35,627 --> 0:26:38,897
The land was here long afore
they come. It's tetched with God.


389
0:26:38,897 --> 0:26:40,298
And he ain't going to
taint it just 'cause


390
0:26:40,298 --> 0:26:42,901
a lot of snakes is
a- crawling in the fallows.


391
0:26:42,901 --> 0:26:45,87
We been poor-hogging long enough.
I got a chance for fancies,


392
0:26:45,87 --> 0:26:47,5
and I'm gonna have them.


393
0:26:47,5 --> 0:26:48,206
That ain't no talk
to your pappy.


394
0:26:48,206 --> 0:26:49,274
I'm talking
to you, too!


395
0:26:49,274 --> 0:26:50,342
I ought to
spank your hide.


396
0:26:50,342 --> 0:26:52,11
You don't need no fotch-on
clothes to be happy.


397
0:26:52,11 --> 0:26:54,913
Just a minute, Dave. I didn't
want to start an argument.


398
0:26:54,913 --> 0:26:56,381
Mr. Tolliver, I don't doubt that you have


399
0:26:56,381 --> 0:26:57,816
every reason
to hate the Falins.


400
0:26:57,816 --> 0:26:59,84
They must have done
you a great wrong...


401
0:26:59,84 --> 0:27:0,952
We don't want no preacher talk from you.


402
0:27:0,952 --> 0:27:3,622
The Tollivers don't like
the Falins and they know why.


403
0:27:3,622 --> 0:27:6,57
And we don't want to be
learned off by no outsiders.


404
0:27:6,57 --> 0:27:7,325
But, Dave,
I'm not trying to...


405
0:27:7,325 --> 0:27:8,526
You saved my life.


406
0:27:8,526 --> 0:27:11,62
You was leaving without a
squeal when we turned you down.


407
0:27:11,62 --> 0:27:13,198
You couldn't have done that
without you was meaning right.


408
0:27:13,198 --> 0:27:20,739
Just don't argue,
that's all.


409
0:27:20,739 --> 0:27:25,377
Where do we sign?


410
0:27:25,377 --> 0:27:46,564
Right here.


411
0:27:46,564 --> 0:27:48,466
The company's
offering you $5,000.


412
0:27:48,466 --> 0:27:50,802
That's a lot of money,
Mr. Falin.


413
0:27:50,802 --> 0:27:52,437
Both sides of our right
of way will still be yours.


414
0:27:52,437 --> 0:27:54,506
It won't interfere
with your farming.


415
0:27:54,506 --> 0:27:55,94
Mr. Thurber here can vouch for our company.


416
0:27:55,94 --> 0:27:57,108
He's kept its books
for years.


417
0:27:57,108 --> 0:27:58,877
Yes. That's right.
Indeed it is.


418
0:27:58,877 --> 0:28:1,312
We don't want no tail-ender
drippings of a Tolliver.


419
0:28:1,312 --> 0:28:2,914
Wade's right. You can't make
butter out of goose grease.


420
0:28:2,914 --> 0:28:5,617
Shut up!


421
0:28:5,617 --> 0:28:7,318
What did
Judd Tolliver say?


422
0:28:7,318 --> 0:28:12,957
Well, he said that...


423
0:28:12,957 --> 0:28:18,29
He said he'd rot before he had
anything to do with a Falin.


424
0:28:18,29 --> 0:28:25,503
That sounds like Judd.


425
0:28:25,503 --> 0:28:28,306
Where do I scratch?


426
0:28:28,306 --> 0:30:3,334
Right here
on the bottom line.


427
0:30:3,334 --> 0:30:5,69
Jack, give us a hand.


428
0:30:5,69 --> 0:30:6,738
You know something
about carpentry.


429
0:30:6,738 --> 0:30:8,206
What's the matter with it?
You're doing all right.


430
0:30:8,206 --> 0:30:9,774
Yeah, I'm not running
any kindergarten.


431
0:30:9,774 --> 0:30:11,276
I got very little use
for children.


432
0:30:11,276 --> 0:30:12,577
In fact
I hate the brats.


433
0:30:12,577 --> 0:30:13,845
Look at me.
Look what I'm doing.


434
0:30:13,845 --> 0:30:16,147
If any of
my friends saw me...


435
0:30:16,147 --> 0:30:17,415
Say, did you send that
check to Judd Tolliver?


436
0:30:17,415 --> 0:30:20,251
Yeah, this morning. Listen.
Would you put a nail in here?


437
0:30:20,251 --> 0:30:45,643
Or... Don't let me
keep you.


438
0:30:45,643 --> 0:30:47,912
Going 'coon hunting, Dave?


439
0:30:47,912 --> 0:30:52,55
Skunk.


440
0:30:52,55 --> 0:30:54,853
Mighty nigh well,
ain't it?


441
0:30:54,853 --> 0:30:56,521
That's why
I'm going hunting.


442
0:30:56,521 --> 0:30:58,456
I don't want you to
fight, Dave.


443
0:30:58,456 --> 0:31:0,124
Leave the Falins be.


444
0:31:0,124 --> 0:31:2,16
There's turning over
to be done.


445
0:31:2,16 --> 0:31:5,63
And I'll be wanting corn
husks for my mattresses.


446
0:31:5,63 --> 0:31:9,1
And we got scrapple to make
and all kinds of things.


447
0:31:9,1 --> 0:31:12,37
You're the only
big boy I've got, Dave.


448
0:31:12,37 --> 0:31:13,671
Families round
about got lots.


449
0:31:13,671 --> 0:31:15,506
Maybe they wouldn't
miss them none.


450
0:31:15,506 --> 0:31:17,842
Maybe they wouldn't.


451
0:31:17,842 --> 0:31:25,283
You're always snorting preachments,
Auntie. You make me sick.


452
0:31:25,283 --> 0:31:28,119
Two pink-eyed doves
sitting in a tree.


453
0:31:28,119 --> 0:31:33,858
One for you
and one for me.


454
0:31:33,858 --> 0:31:35,93
Dave.


455
0:31:35,93 --> 0:31:36,794
My eggs.


456
0:31:36,794 --> 0:31:42,867
Ma! Pa! Dave!
We just got a letter.


457
0:31:42,867 --> 0:31:45,57
We just got a letter.


458
0:31:45,57 --> 0:31:47,438
Pa. A letter.


459
0:31:47,438 --> 0:31:49,14
Juny.


460
0:31:49,14 --> 0:31:50,642
We just got a letter.


461
0:31:50,642 --> 0:31:54,379
A man gave to me
up the road.


462
0:31:54,379 --> 0:31:55,947
Ma, look!


463
0:31:55,947 --> 0:31:58,449
You act like
we never got one before.


464
0:31:58,449 --> 0:32:0,752
We got one when Dave come to live with us


465
0:32:0,752 --> 0:32:4,355
and then we got
another one when...


466
0:32:4,355 --> 0:32:5,523
Who's it for?


467
0:32:5,523 --> 0:32:7,458
Whoever it's writ
to on the front.


468
0:32:7,458 --> 0:32:10,161
Sure enough.


469
0:32:10,161 --> 0:32:11,93
Well, might as well
open it.


470
0:32:11,93 --> 0:32:14,666
What for? We ain't going to be no better off.


471
0:32:14,666 --> 0:32:16,367
Well, you ain't
much help.


472
0:32:16,367 --> 0:32:37,822
Open her up
anyway, Judd.


473
0:32:37,822 --> 0:32:39,824
It's from
the coal company. See?


474
0:32:39,824 --> 0:32:42,76
There's a picture
of a mine on it.


475
0:32:42,76 --> 0:32:45,53
$5,000.


476
0:32:45,53 --> 0:32:49,834
It's just
a piece of paper.


477
0:32:49,834 --> 0:32:51,102
This here's a check.


478
0:32:51,102 --> 0:32:53,104
I seen one once
in Gaptown.


479
0:32:53,104 --> 0:32:55,406
Folks, we're richer
than cream cheese.


480
0:32:55,406 --> 0:32:58,42
And I can get the things
I want, can't I, Pappy?


481
0:32:58,42 --> 0:33:0,611
Now, now, now.
Not so jumpy.


482
0:33:0,611 --> 0:33:2,46
There's one thing
we got to get


483
0:33:2,46 --> 0:33:4,82
more important
than that first,


484
0:33:4,82 --> 0:33:8,653
and that's
a new dress for Melissa.


485
0:33:8,653 --> 0:33:9,988
Oh! Judd.


486
0:33:9,988 --> 0:33:12,9
You sure got it
coming to you, Mammy.


487
0:33:12,9 --> 0:33:13,992
With pearl buttons it'll
have. Won't it, Pappy?


488
0:33:13,992 --> 0:33:16,26
Yeah, pearl buttons.
And the next thing


489
0:33:16,26 --> 0:33:21,532
we got to get is hat
and shoes for Mammy.


490
0:33:21,532 --> 0:33:26,471
It just...
You're making me cry.


491
